"M'Ethingia was not only passionate about the unity of Ameru but also Kenya and Africa. We travelled with him several times to Libya and Nigeria in the bid to have a united Africa," Mr Rutere said.
M'Ethingia will also be remembered for slapping prominent Meru politicians, including Governor Kiraitu Murungi and former Finance minister David Mwiraria, with hefty fines for going against the ideals of Njuri Ncheke.
It was during his tenure that Njuri Ncheke asked former president Mwai Kibaki to pay a goat after former First Lady Lucy Kibaki allegedly slapped former Imenti Central MP Gitobu Imanyara.
M'Ethingia handed over the leadership mantle to Mr Linus Kathera in December last year after four years of wrangling that created two factions of Njuri Ncheke.
The two factions entered an out-of-court settlement in April 2019, leading to a unity pact where leaders from both factions were given positions in an expanded leadership of the Supreme Council of Njuri Ncheke.

